,{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97443","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97443"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old woman presents with a 30-minute history of rapid palpitations associated with shortness of breath and chest discomfort. This came on shortly after she had gone outside for a run. On examination her heart rate is 220/min with a blood pressure of 86/40 mmHg. Her ECG is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Percutaneous coronary intervention","Thrombolysis","DC cardioversion","IV adenosine","Vagal manoeuvre"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u2019s clinical presentation (palpitations, chest pain, dyspnoea) and ECG are consistent with supraventricular tachycardia (SVT).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFeatures on an ECG which are suggestive of SVT include a heart rate greater than 100/min (typically greater than 150/min), narrow complex tachyarrhythmia (QRS \u0026lt;120ms) and a regularly regular rhythm. There may also be non-specific ST changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient exhibits signs of haemodynamically unstable SVT, which include hypotension. As this patient is haemodynamically unstable, the most appropriate initial management is \u003Cstrong\u003EDC cardioversion\u003C/strong\u003E for prompt termination of the arrhythmia.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EHowever, if the patient were haemodynamically stable, \u003Cstrong\u003Evagal manoeuvres\u003C/strong\u003E, such as the Valsalva manouvre or carotid sinus massage, would be the first-line acute treatment. If refractory, \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous adenosine\u003C/strong\u003E could be a potential management option.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELong-term management of SVTs will include either antiarrhythmic medications (beta blockers or calcium channel blockers) or curative catheter ablation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPercutaneous coronary intervention \u003C/strong\u003Eis the definitive treatment option for patients presenting with STEMI. \u003Cstrong\u003EThrombolysis \u003C/strong\u003Etreatment, via tenecteplase or alteplase administration,\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eis provided to STEMI patients if access to PCI is not readily available within 90 minutes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe large majority of patients who suffer from occasional SVT will need neither antiarrhythmics nor catheter ablation with these two options being generally reserved for those suffering repeated or intolerable episodes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["DC cardioversion is used for termination of SVT in patients with haemodynamic compromise.","Vasovagal manoeuvres and IV adenosine are used for acute treatment of SVT in  haemodynamically stable patients."],"references":["Paroxysmal supraventricular tachycardia [published 2018 Mar]. In: Therapeutic Guidelines [digital]. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2018 Mar. \u003Chttps://www.tg.org.au\u003E","Acute coronary syndromes [published 2018 Mar]. In: Therapeutic Guidelines [digital]. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2018 Mar. \u003Chttps://www.tg.org.au\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80053"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11411"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18418"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18418"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9a8a116b-f9fe-43be-a774-5aafac3a8669.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9a8a116b-f9fe-43be-a774-5aafac3a8669.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":355}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80053"},"attr